    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I was thinking about which method to use though. If I use Min-Max scaling, it seems like one massive outlier could totally squash all my other data points into a tiny range. Is standardization usually a better way to manage that, or is it just a different way of organizing the distribution?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Standardization is generally the better choice for K-Nearest Neighbors, especially when you have outliers, because it uses **Z-scores** (mean and standard deviation) rather than raw min/max values.\n\nThink of it this way: Min-Max scaling is like measuring everyone's height in inches, where a single giant person (an outlier) makes everyone else look tiny, effectively squashing the data. Standardization, on the other hand, is like measuring everyone's height relative to their own group's average and spread. If one person is 10 feet tall, they are just \"10 standard deviations away\" from the average, which is a very specific, mathematically defined distance that doesn't get compressed by the presence of other tall people.\n\nHowever, if you have a **normal distribution** (bell curve) and no extreme outliers, Min-Max scaling can actually work fine and is sometimes preferred because it guarantees a fixed range (e.g., 0 to 1), which can be slightly more stable for certain algorithms. But for KNN, standardization is usually the safer bet to ensure that a single outlier doesn't accidentally become the \"nearest neighbor\" for everyone else.\n\n**In short:** Standard",
      "source": "target",
